  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws, conventions, and frameworks aimed at combating money laundering. These efforts are led by global organizations and intergovernmental bodies to create a coordinated approach to preventing financial crimes. Here are the key international mechanisms:\n\n### 1. **United Nations Conventions**\n   - **UN Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988)** (Vienna Convention): The first international treaty to criminalize money laundering, particularly in relation to drug trafficking.\n   - **UN Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime (2000)** (Palermo Convention): Expands anti-money laundering (AML) efforts to include proceeds from all serious crimes, not just drug trafficking.\n   - **UN Convention Against Corruption (2003)** (Merida Convention): Focuses on preventing and combating corruption, including measures to detect and prosecute money laundering linked to corrupt activities.\n\n### 2. **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**\n   - The FATF is the leading intergovernmental body that sets global standards for combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and other related threats to the integrity of the international financial system.\n   - **FATF Recommendations (2012)**: The 40 Recommendations provide a comprehensive framework for AML and counter-terrorist financing (CTF) measures. These recommendations are widely adopted by countries worldwide.\n   - FATF also issues **blacklists** and **greylists** of countries that fail to implement effective AML measures, which can lead to economic sanctions or restrictions.\n\n### 3. **European Union Directives**\n   - The EU has implemented several Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLD) to harmonize AML efforts across member states:\n     - **Sixth Anti-Money Laundering Directive (AMLD6)**: Strengthens penalties, expands the definition of predicate offenses, and imposes stricter requirements on beneficial ownership transparency.\n\n### 4. **Basel Committee on Banking Supervision**\n   - The Basel Committee has issued guidelines for banks to implement effective AML measures, focusing on customer due diligence (CDD), risk management, and suspicious transaction reporting.\n\n### 5. **Other Regional Bodies**\n   - **Egmont Group**: Facilitates international cooperation among Financial Intelligence Units (FIUs) to combat money laundering and terrorist financing.\n   - **APG (Asia/Pacific Group on Money Laundering)**: A regional body that promotes AML efforts in the Asia-Pacific region.\n\n### 6. **Bilateral and Multilateral Agreements**\n   - Many countries have entered into mutual legal assistance treaties (MLATs) and other agreements to cooperate in investigating and prosecuting money laundering cases.\n\n### Key Principles of International AML Laws\n   - **Criminalization of Money Laundering**: Making money laundering a criminal offense.\n   - **Customer Due Diligence (CDD)**: Identifying and verifying customers to prevent illicit transactions.\n   - **Reporting Suspicious Transactions**: Obligations for financial institutions to report suspicious activities.\n   - **Freezing and Confiscation of Assets**: Allowing authorities to seize and freeze illicit funds.\n   - **International Cooperation**: Sharing information and coordinating investigations across borders.\n\n### Enforcement and Compliance\nCountries are expected to implement these international standards into their national laws. Failure to comply can result in sanctions, reputational damage, and exclusion from the global financial system.\n\nIn summary, international laws against money laundering exist through various treaties, conventions, and frameworks, with the FATF playing a central role in setting and monitoring global AML standards.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
